{
  "answer": "**In Cynewulf's *Juliana* (Chapter 1), the demon—appearing as an angel to tempt the imprisoned saint—is seized by Juliana at God's command and forced to confess his crimes.**[^1]\n\n**During this interrogation, the demon recounts his role in tempting humanity from the beginning, explicitly claiming responsibility for Adam and Eve's fall:**\n\n> ...the first people, **Adam and Eve**, from whom I tore life, and **taught them to forsake the Lord’s love**, His eternal grace, their bright, blessed home, so that misery became their lot for life, and for their children also, the darkest of deeds.[^2]\n\n**This occurs amid a longer confession of deceiving biblical figures (e.g., Pilate, Nero) and saints, emphasizing the demon's ancient malice.**[^3] The speech underscores themes of demonic temptation and divine protection in Anglo-Saxon hagiography.\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, [Chapter 1](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/).\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/#p-15a5a2).\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, [paragraphs](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/#p-a370d7).",
